(140, 1, '2009-06-12 01:15:11', '2009-06-11 13:15:11', '<p>You''re reading this, which means that I don''t have to tell you that Urban Legend web design has re-launched its site.</p>\r\n<p>This occasionally-updated page will feature pieces of news, as well as pointers to interesting sites, and observations.</p>\r\n<p>I''ll concentrate on issues revolving around web design and development, especially as it relates to website owners, rather than website developers. </p>\r\n<p>There''ll also be tips and tricks for non-specialist website content managers - i.e. those who want to update their own sites.</p>\r\n<p>This site itself, and some clients'' sites, are built on the Wordpress engine, so it makes sense for the above-named tips to lean toward working with Wordpress.</p>\r\n<p>Check back here for updates.</p>', 'Hello !', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '33-revision-6', '', '', '2009-06-12 01:15:11', '2009-06-11 13:15:11', '', 33, 'http://urbanlegend.co.nz/2009/06/33-revision-6/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(141, 1, '2009-09-16 00:01:35', '2009-09-15 12:01:35', '<p>You''re reading this, which means that Urban Legend web has re-launched its site.</p>\n<p>This occasionally-updated page will feature;</p>\n<ul>\n    <li>tips and tricks for non-specialist website content managers - i.e. those who want to update their own sites. Most of these will be to do with <a href="http://wordpress.org" target="newone" title="visit Wordpress.org - opens in new window">Wordpress</a>. This site itself, and some clients'' sites, are built on the Wordpress engine, so it makes sense for the above-named tips to lean toward working with Wordpress.</li>\n    <li>news snippets related to the web and web design</li>\n    <li>occasional pointers to interesting sites, and observations.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Check back here for updates.</p>', 'Hello !', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '33-autosave', '', '', '2009-09-16 00:01:35', '2009-09-15 12:01:35', '', 33, 'http://urbanlegend.co.nz/2009/09/33-autosave/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(532, 1, '2010-08-31 23:50:13', '2010-08-31 11:50:13', '<p>This site was designed by Helen Smith of <a href="http://www.mcgovern.co.nz/" title="McGovern &amp; Associates - opens in new window" target="newone">McGovern &amp; Associates</a>, and hand-coded from supplied files. It is an early example - 2005 - of using  <dfn title="Cascading Style Sheets">CSS</dfn> for layout and XHTML. The site is driven by an in-house content management system.</p>', 'Katherine Mansfield House', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '156-revision-2', '', '', '2010-08-31 23:50:13', '2010-08-31 11:50:13', '', 156, 'http://urbanlegendweb.co.nz/2010/08/156-revision-2/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(533, 1, '2010-09-06 22:46:33', '2010-09-06 10:46:33', '<p>I''ve been snuffling around in my archives, dusting off long-forgotten back-up CDs and such, and found an interesting&nbsp; <a title="Palette Picker" href="/colorpicker/">wee toy</a> I''d almost forgotten writing.</p>\r\n<p>It''s a basic <a href="/colorpicker/">palette picker</a>, written as a web-page, which allows the user to choose a web-page colour scheme from the <a title="Visibone''s 216-colour chart - opens in new window" target="newone" href="http://www.visibone.com/colorlab/">216 basic colours</a>.</p>\r\n<p>There are four colour-able areas. You fill them by clicking a colour from the panel on the left, and then in one of the colour-able areas. A cookie will save the scheme you decided on, and CSS codes for the color are given.</p>\r\n<p>I&nbsp;did say it''s basic :&nbsp;I wrote it in <strong>2002</strong>, using Javascript,&nbsp; before the days of JQuery. The code is embedded rather than linked, so it''s easy to see (&nbsp;and modify if you choose ).</p>\r\n<p>Who knows, it may be useful, but probably more likely a 5-minute diversion. <a href="/colorpicker/" title="try out the palette picker">Have at it</a>!</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'The Palette Picker', 0, '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'palett-picker', '', '', '2010-10-19 14:39:02', '2010-10-19 02:39:02', '', 0, 'http://urbanlegendweb.co.nz/?p=533', 0, 'post', '', 0),
